from Tamiya Ryouko.

237
00:14:04.134 --> 00:14:06.262 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
She must be somewhere
behind that building.

238
00:14:06.345 --> 00:14:09.431 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
Don't tell me she's now
a university lecturer

239
00:14:09.515 --> 00:14:11.267 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
after her stint as a high school teacher.

240
00:14:12.226 --> 00:14:16.772 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:10.00% 
"Altruism" is behavior undertaken
for the benefit of another.

241
00:14:16.855 --> 00:14:18.732 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
It is the opposite of "selfishness".

242
00:14:18.816 --> 00:14:21.151 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
At first glance, altruistic behavior
poses no advantage for the self.

243
00:14:21.235 --> 00:14:24.697 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
Rather, it is behavior
that helps others despite posing

244
00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:26.407 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
a distinct disadvantage to the self.

245
00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:28.158 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
-It is perhaps not so rareâ€¦
-It's a baby!

246
00:14:28.242 --> 00:14:29.618 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
-â€¦among human beings,
-So cute.

247
00:14:31.078 --> 00:14:33.414 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
â€¦but altruistic behavior
has also been observed

248
00:14:33.497 --> 00:14:37.585 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
among a number of animal species.

249
00:14:37.668 --> 00:14:40.796 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
For example, honeybees
will sacrifice themselves

250
00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:45.009 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
to protect the hive when predators appear.

251
00:14:45.092 --> 00:14:47.511 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
This behavior may be instinctive.

252
00:14:47.595 --> 00:14:50.264 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
However, there exists
a prime example of behavior

253
00:14:50.347 --> 00:14:53.017 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
that does not serve
to protect one's own species.

254
00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:55.019 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
Infanticide.

255
00:14:55.686 --> 00:14:59.273 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
Why do animals kill offspring
of their own species?

256
00:14:59.356 --> 00:15:05.070 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
The prevailing theory in recent years
is the "selfish gene".

257
00:15:05.154 --> 00:15:10.034 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
In a nutshell, the body of an animal
is merely its DNA's puppet.

258
00:15:10.117 --> 00:15:12.202 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
What matters is not its species but itself

259
00:15:12.286 --> 00:15:16.290 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
and its own offspring
who will inherit its DNA.

260
00:15:16.373 --> 00:15:18.542 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
If we apply this theory more broadly,

261
00:15:18.626 --> 00:15:20.628 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
it can explain a wide variety
of altruistic behavior,

262
00:15:20.711 --> 00:15:23.797 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
such as caring for others in a herd,

263
00:15:23.881 --> 00:15:25.633 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
familial love, marital love,

264
00:15:25.716 --> 00:15:29.303 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
and even maternal love.

265
00:15:29.970 --> 00:15:33.933 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
This would mean that there is
no such thing as compassion or love.

266
00:15:34.016 --> 00:15:36.352 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
All behavior that appears
to stem from love is,

267
00:15:36.435 --> 00:15:41.315 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
in fact, merely behavior to better
the transmission of an individual's DNA.

268
00:15:41.398 --> 00:15:44.860 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
Of course, this theory
is not without its problems.

269
00:15:44.944 --> 00:15:49.281 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
There are multiple cases observed
in nature where animals help others

270
00:15:49.365 --> 00:15:52.576 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
who will have no impact
on the transmission of their own DNA

271
00:15:52.660 --> 00:15:55.829 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
and even others who are
of an entirely different species.

272
00:15:55.913 --> 00:15:57.122 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
In addition,

273
00:15:57.206 --> 00:15:59.917 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
it's uncertain whether complex
human thought

274
00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.586 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
can be captured in full by this theory.

275
00:16:03.420 --> 00:16:04.254 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>In that sense,</i>

276
00:16:04.338 --> 00:16:07.967 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>it may be interesting to consider</i>
<i>whether human efforts in the realm</i>

277
00:16:08.050 --> 00:16:09.969 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>of environmental and nature conservation</i>

278
00:16:10.052 --> 00:16:13.639 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>are altruistic or selfish in nature.</i>

279
00:16:15.474 --> 00:16:16.850 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>It's almost time.</i>

280
